Project Overview

The original study examined differences in selective trade-offs and responses to predation in two closely related and syntopic treefrog species: Agalychnis callidryas and A. spurrelli. The study performed field surveys to collect data on natural spontaneous hatching timings and natural predation on egg clutches of the two species. Authors also performed predation experiments using snakes for predation on eggs and fish for predation on hatchlings.

Their specific null hypotheses were outlined explicitly, â(1) both species experience similar levels of egg predation; (2) they have the same pattern of undisturbed or spontaneous hatching; (3) their escape hatching responses to snake attack and flooding are similar; and (4) early hatching increases vulnerability to aquatic predators in A. spurrelli, as it does in A. callidryas.â

This paper used multiple data sets from various authors. All data was collected in the field, but in different years and by different authors. They performed a suite of statistical analysis, but the main ones were as follows:

  1. âThe overall proportion of monitored clutches predated in the field, escape hatching success in snake predation experiments, and proportion of hatchlings surviving Wsh predation were all analysed using generalized linear models with an underlying binomial distribution and a logit link function in PROC GENMOD.â

  2. âWe performed a log-linear analysis of the number of clutches of each species that were predated and undisturbed on each of 16 nights when both were present. Model parameters were estimated through maximum likelihood using PROC CATMOD, assuming an underlying Poisson distribution.â

  3. âWe tested for effects of embryo development on escape success in snake attacks using generalized linear models.â

  4. âThe hatching response of A. spurrelli to underwater submergence was tested against its unflooded controls by Wtting a Cox regression model using PROC PHREGâ

  5. âThe effects of hatching age on the proportion of hatchlings surviving in the fish predation experiments was analysed with a generalized linear model, including fish size as a covariate.â

Note: I will be reanalyzing data for data sets which I was able to obtain. I will reproduce analysis for the following:

  1. GLMs on field predation observations, snake predation experiments, and fish predation experiments; including the corresponding data manipulation, data summarization and descriptive statistical analysis, and visualization of each.

  2. GLM to test for effects of age on escape success

  3. GLM to test for effects of age and fish size on hatchling survival

So lets get started!

Proportion of predated clutches

Next, lets look at the overall proportion of predated clutches for each species and compare them using a test of equal proportions:

Note: since the data frame I obtained doesnât have info about the total number of observed clutches, we need to calculate the total N for each species. We can âback calculateâ this since we know the proportion of predated clutches for each species from the data reported in the paper, 0.40 and 0.48 for callidryas and spurrelli respectively.

length(d$species[d$species=="callidryas"]) #number of predated clutches for callidryas
## [1] 182
Ncalidryas= 182 *.40
Ncalidryas
## [1] 72.8
length(d$species[d$species=="spurrelli"]) #number of predated clutches for spurrelli
## [1] 19
Nspurrelli= 19 *.48
Nspurrelli
## [1] 9.12
#then incorporating these numbers into a two sample proportion test:
prop.test(x=c(73,9), n=c(182,19)) #clearly the proportions predated for each species were not significaly different from each other
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions with continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  c(73, 9) out of c(182, 19)
## X-squared = 0.13492, df = 1, p-value = 0.7134
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3371813  0.1920107
## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2 
## 0.4010989 0.4736842

library(ggplot2)

gc= ggplot(data=mphc, aes(x=day_time, y=mean_prop)) + geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(fill=time_of_day)) #use barplots w/time of day filled w/color
gc= gc + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean_prop-SE, ymax=mean_prop+SE), width=.2, position=position_dodge(.9), color="black") #add black error bars
gc= gc + labs(x= "Age (days)", y= "Sponanteous hatching (proportion hatched eggs)") #make labels for axis
gc= gc + theme_bw(base_size = 11, base_family = "Times") #make theme in Times New Roman and b/w
gc= gc + annotate("text", x = 2, y = 0.5, label = "(b) A. callidryas", fontface= "italic") #add italicized text to figure!
gc= gc + scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "black")) # change "fills" to blue for day and black for night
gc

#and again same for spurrelli
